text: Great place to stay for Fishermen's Warf.  It is $$$ but worth it. Staff are excellent. Like they say "you get what you pay for". Excellent stay.

name: Erik Carlson
text: Service was good, rooms are nice but the bathroom configuration is strange and small. Rooms are very susceptible to noise pollution from other rooms. Location is excellent, very close to pier 39 and the tour busses.

name: Paula Long
text: Fantastic staff especially to my furbaby Molly

name: Silvia Zexto
text: My family and I loved this hotel. Very clean. Maggie at the front desk is quiet possibly the most friendly person we've meet in a long time. Everyone we met was friendly.

name: Dave Cholger
text: Great little place to stay right in fisherman's wharf

name: Patrick Warren
text: Sheraton is always been low for high-quality luxury hotels this hotel wasn‚Äôt one of my better stays at Sheraton as it was a very old hotel but it still was clean staff was nice location was great but share to does do it‚Äôs best

name: Emily Belcher
text: The rooms are mediocre. It's a pain to get Ubers to find the entrance. Nice location for the pier, terrible for eating out and downtown access. Entrance way is quite under par, but it's ok.

name: Jeff Yeo
text: Good location, friendly staff who are very helpful. They still practice make a green choice which is great ! The room decor is a little dated but I guess it adds to the charm. The down side is the paper thin walls, you can hear traffic and people walking around and talking. Bring your ear plug along. Parking onsite is 56+ usd with unlimited re-entry which is pretty expensive.

name: Ankush Kumar
text: Great location. Nearby to fisherman's wharf and in n out burgers. Had just a night of stay so could not explore much but certainly a good option for stay in SFO. Got it from hotwire so was a steal for me. Provided luggage storage service which gave me time to go around SFO after checking out. One improvement I would like is a water bottle at time of check in. Would visit again.

name: Ernest Figueroa
text: Very nice hotel. Staff was and helpful. The only thing that bothered me was the 56$ for parking

name: Cheyenne Bronson
text: Unfriendly staff and on top of an overpriced room you also are forced to pay 75 bucks for parking. Not returning.

name: Nathan Barranco
text: The staff really made this place enjoyable. They were beyond helpful. Had a great stay!

name: Jera F
text: The location of the hotel is very convenient and the rooms are great with awesome amenities, also the serviy is perfect. I recommend it because is near to stores and touristic points are close to it.

name: Meg Smith
text: We had a comfortable stay at this Sheraton. Rooms are spacious and cheerfully decorated, hotel staff are courteous and solicitous, the location is great for those looking to be central to tourist hot spots. Internet and other "amenities" come at a very high price.

name: Dan Menoher
text: The hotel is a typical big box hotel, but my room was substandard. The hotel has a great location being only 5-10 mins from pier 39. The staff was very nice and helpful. Overall, I would not stay there with my family again cause of the sleep issues the light and the noise caused. I might stay there again for business, but only cause the location was very nice. As far as negatives door to my room didnt have a seal, so the hall lights were very bright at night! There was a exhaust fan on the roof next to my room which was very loud and would wake up my new born every time it turned on. I called the front desk to ask for empty wine glasses, they said they would have to charge me.

name: Dr. Anthony Conde MD MPH
text: Limited room service hours but you are paying to stay walking distance to the Pier. Everything is walking distance including good restaurants and supermarket and pharmacy.

name: John Carpentier
text: Convenient location, fairly plain decor and rooms

name: Steven Seabron
text: Close to everything and very comfortable

name: Daniel Th
text: Upscale Sheraton hotel in Fisherman's Wharf area. Rooms are spacious and facilities are worth the money spent. This is close to Pier 39 and other happening places.

name: Darren Swan
text: Great location near to the waterfront. Very friendly staff.

name: Kathy McKenzie
text: Very convenient to Fisherman's Wharf, small bar and great heater/fireplace seating outside along with great service. Downfall, $50 per day parking but that's San Francisco anyway.

name: Cary Simmons
text: Good place to stay. Quite and clean. Breakfast was expensive, so we went elsewhere to eat.

name: Nathan Anderson
text: Nice place. Recommend not being on the street side if you have trouble sleeping. Especially the side with the union civic center or whatever it was called.

name: Sofia Gunawan
text: A very family friendly hotel that still leaves the red carpet treatment out for singletons traveling on a modest budget.

name: Data Jack
text: A great hotel, for the most part. Room service is very pricey. Also both room service and the restaurant had surprisingly unfriendly menus for vegetarians. I found myself ordering from UberEats daily. But otherwise it was a pleasant stay. Great location too.

name: Ankush Kumar
text: Great location. Nearby to fisherman's wharf and in n out burgers. Had just a night of stay so could not explore much but certainly a good option for stay in SFO. Got it from hotwire so was a steal for me. Provided luggage storage service which gave me time to go around SFO after checking out. One improvement I would like is a water bottle at time of check in. Would visit again.

name: Ardeshir Ghoreishi
text: Clean... Nice staff... It seems that they choose to not have all Sheraton standards in this hotel.... I didn't like people buying thir own bottle of liquor or beer and drinking outside by the fire.... It seemed that this is very normally becuse Sheraton even provides you with the glasses.... It just got really not nice... When every body off street can gather and do this....

name: Emily Belcher
text: The rooms are mediocre. It's a pain to get Ubers to find the entrance. Nice location for the pier, terrible for eating out and downtown access. Entrance way is quite under par, but it's ok.

name: Nathan Anderson
text: Nice place. Recommend not being on the street side if you have trouble sleeping. Especially the side with the union civic center or whatever it was called.

name: Darren Swan
text: Great location near to the waterfront. Very friendly staff.

name: Philip Tagatac
text:
5/5 stars with ONE flaw: parking.

The Pros:
Excellent guest service, kind staff and overall a pleasant experience getting to the room. The keycard sensor on the three elevators adjacent to the lobby are somewhat finicky, so you *might* have to swipe your card another time to make sure it scans. Walking to the rooms, the scent was neutral (unless you pass a cleaning card, which in that case it smells like ammonia), and the floors were clean.

Like most chain hotels, you will expect to see crisp, unwrinkled bedsheets and pillowcases, which is what I saw, and a clean bathroom. Overall, 5/5 for the room. I had 0 issues with noise, as my room was positioned looking over where guest would be dropped off via taxi/Uber/Lyft.

As far as convenience goes, this place is PERFECT for the first time traveler to SF. Safeway and CVS are literally a 30 second walk across the street, and Fisherman's Wharf is only a 5 minute walk from the Sheraton. Great breakfast and lunch places are available within 5-10 minutes walking, and if you need groceries, Trader Joes and Safeway (again) is a short jump, skip and a walk away.

My ONE flaw with this place is parking. At roughly $70 per night, it hurts a doctoral student's budget. Granted, $70 will allow you to take your car in and out as many times as you like, but if you're in the city, you tend NOT to drive your car in and out. My suggestion is to park upstairs at the Safeway. You won't be able to take your car out unlimited times, BUT they will only charge you $36 a night. Take it with a grain of salt, but I'd rather park across the street for two nights for the price of one at the Sheraton. I left my car there overnight for two nights, and had 0 issues. It's guarded and well lit as well. So if you don't need to move your car, definitely consider parking at the Safeway.

Again, great location for first timers to the city. Convenient to touristy areas, and not too far of a drive to downtown.

name: Freddy Marcel-Marcum
text:
I'm giving this hotel one star not because of the actual facilities, they seem pretty nice actually. No, I'm giving the Sheraton Fisherman's Wharf a thumbs down because of a rather ugly incident that took place last night involving a doorman and a family group of 20 tourists from Newcastle, Australia around 7pm, 28 December.

I'm an airport shuttle driver, my boss calls me just as I'm finishing a sixteen hour shift, hey, go to the hotel, couple of families going to the Westin by the airport, you and another driver handle it, good luck. Cool, I can manage that. Show up, and immediately am met by a doorman, some sort of Pakistani guy, five-six, balding, who has made it clear I'm not getting out of my vehicle until I agree to "take care of him", which in his rapid-fire thickly accented English basically came down to pulling a scam by inflating the agreed upon rate of $60 per vehicle to $90, claiming to the guests there were no other airport shuttles available and he was essentially saving the day by calling us. I'm a large Czechoslovak man, with that look in his eye and especially being born under communism, I don't like bribery, out of my way.
NOW, I've been driving commercially since I was a junior in high school off and on, three different continents, Iraq, driving a school bus in college, limos, I've had half of Hollywood in my backseat, and I love a good hustle, but lying to guests? Lying to people you're supposed to be assisting? I don't do that. My hustle is showing up on time and driving safely, or showing passengers where they can get weed or cheap concert tickets in San Francisco, I deal with graft and hustling every day, it goes with the job but dude, this guy came in last at Hustler U, and probably never paid off his student loan. He really thought he was going to scam two families headed by oil rig men? World travellers like those families? And then whining about tips from the fathers? Hell I give him credit for trying, that's like me driving Formula 1 expecting to win first place. We had a good laugh about it on the way to the airport. What wasn't so funny was the fact this guy called his buddy with a Chrysler van and CRAMMED nine people in a six-passenger vehicle and whisked them off before the other driver from my company with a nine-passenger vehicle could arrive. There was no hurry to get them out, they weren't even catching a flight, but he was so greedy he was willing to break all kinds of SFMTA and California vehicle laws in order to get a cash kickback it was alarming. Also, a flat rate for medallion holding taxi drivers in San Francisco to the airport is $35, not the $60 you told them it was. This hotel isn't a jihadist small arms bazaar, you don't lie and swindle people for what is essentially what you make in an hour. And you didn't even help them with their suitcases and luggage, you let the women do it instead? What a gentleman.
Buddy, as far as being taken care of, you need to take care of guests, ESPECIALLY if they include women and girls and young children in prams, and forget your wallet. You make probably four times salary what I do, especially in this season, in a safe heated building, and I'm not giving you a dime for doing what Sheraton International hired you to do. You can screw over gullible newlyweds from Iowa or tourists who don't speak English, nobody can stop you, but don't try to hustle a hustler or people accustomed to guys like you, you'll fail every time, and I am forwarding this to corporate.

Remember the Golden Rule of hustling bud: it's only a hustle if you're the only one in on it and the person being hustled thinks they're the one coming out on top and has no idea what's really going on. Anything else is just ripping off tourists, and here in the United States we look down on that hard.

name: Ardeshir Ghoreishi
text: Clean... Nice staff... It seems that they choose to not have all Sheraton standards in this hotel.... name: Louise Moloney
text: The only 4 star thing about this hotel is the price, which is high. However everything else is extra e.g. high speed internet is 19 dollars but is NOT high speed. Watch out that self parking is not available for larger SUV so we had to use valet parking at 69 dollars a day. Hotel room was not clean (old blueberry under desk & other fluff around the carpet) & the bathroom is tiny. Location is good for fisherman's wharf, Safeway supermarket & cable car. However we left 1 day early & would choose somewhere else next time (e.g. we've stayed at the Holiday Inn down the road which is much more dated but somehow we didn't feel so ripped off)

name: Andrew Crowley
text: Nice rooms, good location but nothing out of the ordinary.

name: Andy Chu
text: Lovely hotel. Nice, clean, and super convenient to everything. Also the free WiFi helps stay connected to everything.

name: Maryanne R
text: The place was nice. Rooms are clean and the check in attendant was very polite and helped us get the type of room and space we needed.

name: Gilbert Yurubi
text: Many great places to eat and drink.  Sites are beautiful. Many great tours to take.

name: Rudy Grajeda
text: Just need a microwave and refrigerator. It was nice and fire places outside patio.

name: Nelu John Tuns

name: Ronni Paterson

name: Tanya B
text: Met up with some friends and loved the decor of the one with the food service area...cozy and quaint

name: Matthew L

name: Carole S
text: Nice staff, clean room and close to the pier.

Me and my wife were here 18th to 22nd November

Hope some day we will return

text: Had a great time this weekend, and it helps when the rooms are ready and clean.

name: Gian Paolo Santopaolo

name: Torsten Keil-Long
text: Its a bit expensive for what you get. First off, to park in their structure, it's $75 (I think per night Also?.. may be wrong about that part I wasn't paying). The hotel plays as upscale, when it's a really generic place... Not worth the cost with parking but hey welcome to SF

name: Luke Andreassen
text: We met some others there for an event. The area was nice. The hallways in some wings were slightly out dated but the rooms seemed nice and lobby was clean and inviting.

name: J ‚ÄúMoToSaKi‚Äù T
text: Good atmosphere, great room, great pool. $62+tax for parking is ridiculous!

name: Jennifer M
text: Nice, clean, modern rooms here.  Close to the piers.  We stayed in an outer facing room and it was a little noisy in the mornings with the cable cars.  The breakfast buffet is overpriced for what you get.  I would recommend staying here, with an inner facing room, and getting meals elsewhere.

name: Varun Dhawan
text: The rooms are really nice and comfortable. Staff is friendly too. Ask for a complimentary bottle of water at the reception. üòä

name: Don Martin
text: Pretty good, a solid 4 stars. Noisey but not as noisey as those along the Embarcadero, close to all the good things, my bathroom was small.

name: arnab bera

name: Stephen K
text: Decent tourist hotel. Expensive buffet, but was comped as a platinum guest. Thin walls means you can hear everything around you in your room. Small showers, small TV but no major complaints.

name: Hsin-I O'Brien

name: Jason Boutte'

name: Luke Andreassen
text: We met some others there for an event. The area was nice. The hallways in some wings were slightly out dated but the rooms seemed nice and lobby was clean and inviting.

name: Kody Andrews
text: the security guard was rude and was treating me differently than others. I was asked to move multoipul times why other people just sat there and waited to pick up their riders. I was the only one asked to move and was given Avery snotty attitude and aggressive behavior for no reason while waiting to take a friend to the airport.. he was rude and very unprofessional.

text: Dependanble place, free wine tasting was a great surprise bonus

name: Amber
text: The location is great. Right within easy walking distance of pier 39 and fisherman's wharf. And easy to get to the cable car for chinatown. However, you hear those cable cars. All. Night. Long. At least you do if on the ground floor which is where I was. The bathroom is tiny. Like the space from the wall to the tub is as wide as the toilet itself. Good luck changing in there and not busting an elbow. And the toilet itself is awful. Tons of water usage with no benefit. Be prepared to sit there waiting to flush a 2nd or 3rd time (and you will be waiting a while as the tank takes forever to fill thanks to using a ton of water in the first place). They do allow pets for no charge which can be good or bad depending on if you have pets or are allergic to them. Overall it's not awful and if you can get a good deal it may be worth it. Just don't get the ground floor if you're a light sleeper.

name: Nick Spencer
text: OK, but not up to standards of other four star hotels. Cafe area in lobby was a bit weird and very over priced. A nice cosy bar would have been better. Key card kept breaking. HVAC system in my room was very noisy, it actually woke me up turning on. Otherwise everything was fine.

name: Jared Dong
text: Our stay at the Sheraton at Fisherman's Wharf was mostly good. The hotel is undergoing an extensive remodel, so almost everything is new. The two things that prevent this hotel from being 5 stars for me: 1) the bed wasn't the most comfortable and 2) we were woken up twice in the middle of the night by people playing extremely loud music, meaning the sound insulation needs work. Overall, it was still a good value.

name: Timothy Mike Parolise
text: Location is great but for what you are getting price is ridiculous. Because its right by the pier prices get jacked up. Because uber is huge in San Francisco its a better option to get a cheaper hotel further from the pier.

name: Varun Dhawan
text: The rooms are really nice and comfortable. Staff is friendly too. Ask for a complimentary bottle of water at the reception. üòä

name: Traci
text: While I had a pleasant stay at this hotel for 3 nights, I have to say, it's a motel in holiday decor. Some areas are updated, like the firepit in the driveway and the lobby, but the rooms themselves are in mixed hallways, just a confusing mix. But, despite being in a tourist area, I found my room to be very quiet, clean and central to everywhere I needed to be on a business trip.

name: John Toledo
text: Beautiful hotel, id say best one on fisherman's wharf, it's walking distance to pier 39 so u won't have to keep taking ur car out of the lot

name: Matt coles
text: Only a couple of problems.  1 you could close the door to the bath room unless you stand in the bath tub. 2 noise from the traffic on the street out side of the room could heard all night long.

name: Brian Jones
text: A great business hotel in the middle of the touristy pr39 District. Chinatown and North Beach the Italian district are all around the corner and a short walk away.

name: Andreas Bildtse
text: Good location, good rooms and always service

name: Heth Mares
text:
Frequently stay in Sheraton's when I travel and this was by far my worst stay experience: Loud from 5 am-12 midnight, pillows & bed were hard & uncomfortable & most of the staff were very distant, short, rude &/or unfriendly when we approached them.

The only positive was the location...right across street from safeway grocery store, around corner from cvs, trader joe's, Starbucks & walgreens & only a 5 min walk to fisherman's wharf, tour bus depots/dispatch & cable car dispatch.

name: Aaron Ho
text: Good experience. Rooms were clean, service was good, and the location was great. Very conveniently located near many attractions.

name: Kim E
text: Rooms and service are fine. However, lots of families with kids seem to stay so very noisy; constant running up and down halls. Noisy outside too. No blackout curtains.

name: Justin Johns

The interior of the hotel is a bit dated but it looked like they'd be rennovating soon. Also none of the rooms have any kind of view. Smoking is not permitted but there was a gentleman smoking on the patio above our room. The old school HVAC unit was sucking in the smokey air and pushing it into our room. That was quite annoying.

text: OK, but not up to standards of other four star hotels. Cafe area in lobby was a bit weird and very over priced. A nice cosy bar would have been better. Key card kept breaking. HVAC system in my room was very noisy, it actually woke me up turning on. Otherwise everything was fine.

All in all the place was ok

text: Had a bad experience, rooms are clean but no better than a cheap hotel. The room we got was on a major street with lots of traffic noise and we must have been next to the dumpster/loading docks big truck backing up all night‚Äã . No refrigerator (it a big deal if you have kids), wifi is pay per device per day. I was told one rate when I checked in and when I checked out it was double. I had to argue with the manager about it then he said that they write the nightly rate on the key card holder, lucky for me I kept it and it was not written on there. So I got it for what I was told up front but the staff was all pissy with me and a huge line had built up and everyone as looking at me like I was the ass.

name: Lana Larue
text: No views. Kinda Pricey! Overall a very Nice experience. üòä

name: Mei Qin (baeqin)
text: The hotel was nice and had a lot of ppaces downstairs to hang out. The lobby had a drink bar for many different types of drinks including coffee nd alcohol. There were nice fire pits outside with seating separated in a smoking and non smoking section. The included amenities were nice, but I didn't stay long enough to really make use of them. The parking was easy to get to and find, but if possible I would recommend not driving there as it is $56 a night for hotel guests and $70 for 24hrs for non hotel guests. The parking ended up being half the cost of the room. Otherwise the hotel staff is friendly and helpful. The line for the lobby isn't well defined. They should really section it off so its clear which way guests shohld line up itherwise you get people just standing haphazardly and cutting others whether intentional or not.

name: Gordon Tan
text: 3 storey hotel witj 2 buildings. The service staffs are very friendly, they greet you whenever they see you. If you are not a SPG member you will not have access to the express lounge which open from 6am to 11pm, they have both cold and hot drinks at the lounge and also snacks like mix nuts etc. Comfortable sofa and chairs to relax while watching TV shows. They also have a courtyard for you to chill. There is a swimming pool and gym as well. The locatin is very near Pier 39, IHOP amd CVS etc.

name: Ali Townsend
text: Rooms feel a little dated and the bathroom area is tiny, but it's totally serviceable for a one or two night stay.

name: Waleed Effendi
text: It was a really pleasant stay at the Sheraton Fishmerman's Wharf Hotel. The employees were really nice and helpful. The hotel provided with free complimentary wifi which was extremely helpful as I am a student and it helped with my studying. The rooms looked really nice and their were a lot of amenities, but I didn't get a chance to go to all of them. I really enjoyed the fireplace with sofas to relax at. I would recommend booking through priceline as I was able to get the booking at a much cheaper price. I would recommend going their if your visting SF for a day or two. The Fisherman's Wharf is within walking distance. Only reason i gave it a 4 star was the cost of parking as they charged $56 for overnight parking but you get in and out privilages. But this is understandable because parking is problem in SF generally.

name: Paul Johns
text: Great Hotel. Parking is higher than a car payment!

name: Robby Rash
text: Clean and nicely updated at a reasonable price. Parking is pricey but it's to be expected in SF. I will be staying here again for sure.

name: Patrick Wynn
text: Pricey for what you get. Inside it has been refurbished in a cool modern style but frankly it seems like cheaper version of aloft. The under-window air conditioner was a little noisy. No free coffee at reception in the morning. Wi-Fi is extra. Good location for fisherman's wharf though.

The parking setup is a bit weird, and it took me a long time to be able to leave since the keys for the parking were nor working... Also, the most expensive parking in the area.

text: If you want to be at Fisherman's Wharf, this is a great option, and consistent with the starwood brand. The hotel staff is extremely friendly and always treats me well.

We were so happy to arrive at the hotel, and to be able to enjoy our...

text: Artisinal is truly an epicurean delight! Entrees were flavorful, choices were great for every palate. Several delightful selections for the first course including octopus and squid. Second course included Alaskan Halibut, Duck and a special cut of ribeye. Several side dishes for sharing, including pomme frites. Finally, desserts were outstanding !

name: Amanda A
text: At $250 a night and almost $70 to park is outrageous.  The room wasnt super clean as i found some hair stuck to the bathroom wall and one in the sink area.

name: Rith Mean
text: Location was great, a few block away from fisherman's wharf. The hotel is clean, and there are firepits outside which is nice if you dont quite want to go to your room but dont really want to go out. There is a safeway right behind them, so its convenient for all of your needs if you forgot something. Plenty of things to do nearby so that is a plus.

name: Franci Pennington

name: Robert Matthew
text: Went for a conference. Clean, well setup, friendly staff, and good coffee and pastries on sale.

name: Zack Martin
text: Parking was expensive and very tight, just over 6ft, $300+/ night, $180 with southwest for really cheesy rooms, and they locked me out from plugging in an HDMI to the TV, and on top of all of this, the WiFi was over $15 per night, and that was just the cheap option. The only good thing was that it was just a couple blocks from pier 39. That's it.

name: Hung Ngo (Daily random)
text: love the walking distant and the included parking. room a little small and cleanliness is questionable, a little smell, but we have a great experience.

name: Maria C.
text: Great service,  comfy rooms.

name: Nancy Mora
text:
We are from Reno, NV and booked this hotel for one night. After the date of the booking a storm was announced from Nevada and part of California. Donner Pass was closed. We called Expedia the  guy who helped us was great he really tried to help us. We said we didn‚Äôt want the money back that if they give us a voucher will be great.

This was the answer from Expedia...

Thank you for contacting Expedia about your cancellation request from your reservation at Sheraton Fisherman's Wharf Hotel.

We have advocated your case with the hotel representative,  however, Sheraton Fisherman's Wharf Hotel has denied your request for a refund as the hotel stick with the cancellation and change policy.

We apologize for the inconvenience.Thank you for choosing Expedia...

The Sheraton shows that doesn't care about their customers. They will not work with you they just want your money. They don't care if you can't make it even if is due to weather!!! Shame on you Sheraton!!

name: K ‚ÄúSlim‚Äù Johnson
text: cost too much for the location and  very few amenities gotta pay to park.

name: James Jefferson
text: For the price, it maybe isn't worth it. It's an ok hotel, good location, but the room rate and parking cost don't match.

name: Nick H
text: Waited for friends. The lobby and outdoor seating area were very nice.

name: Steven Brothers
text: Great location right next to the wharf.  Rooms were recently remodeled, so thats a plus.  Parking is outrageous but I was able to find free sunday parking a few blocks south.  Got the room for only $70 on priceline!

name: Joy Dillon
text: Room was clean. Central location which was nice. No free WiFi in our room like our confirmation stated.

name: Artem Petukhov
text: Great hotel and rooms, but no free wi fi in the hotel, only if you seat in the lobby

name: Bill Rank
text: Great value for the location...nothing amazing the building itself though. Nice lobby for working, hanging, etc.

name: Gary Ahluwalia
text: Located central to many attractions!! Room was neat and clean and loved their service

name: Premier Images
text: What a great place to stay in the Wharf

name: Peter D
text: Air conditioning unit is right next to the bed and it would randomly turn on during a cold night, blowing cold air right onto my face- I think because the thermostat is wireless and separate from the HVAC unit which is installed into the window.  May be the adjacent room's wireless thermostat kept turning mine on?  Who knows, I was in room 3222.  Also the floors/ceilings are not robust.  I literally heard every movement of the occupants in the room above me as they were walking around at 6am.  The hotel also charges exorbitant fees ($17.99 per day) for in-room wi-fi.  The fee is waived if you sign up for their SPG rewards program.  I'm already a member, but I didn't book through their app, so I wasn't able to get free internet.  Not a huge deal, but really makes me feel their rewards program is worthless because most middle class people don't stay exclusively at one hotel chain in 2017.  You can collect $5 worth of points for not getting room service.  But seriously, you'll probably lose that benefit if you book at regular rates through their app or website.  It's also very unappealing to get price-gouged on something as trivial as internet.  Overall, the stay was not worth it at all.  The free internet that they do provide is in the lobby, where it gets crowded with people using it and also slows down your connection.  Not a 4-star hotel experience at all.  No wonder they were Pricelining at ~$92 when other 4-star hotels were at $250 for that particular week.  Also, the front desk wasn't very friendly, I tried to push checkout to 2pm because of the AC, but they gave me until 1pm saying they were at capacity.  Right....sure....at $86/night on Priceline you're at full capacity...such BS. Having the "engineer" come up to examine your AC unit at 9am because you couldn't sleep isn't my idea of a comfortable 4-star stay.  Thankfully, the engineers were able to manually shut it off.  I have slept better in a 1-star hostel and probably would have gotten complimentary wi-fi.  Almost all hotels in 2017 in San Francisco offer complimentary internet. Complete waste of money.

name: Fadil Karim
text:
My stay was very pleasurable at this sheraton.
Pros:
Staff was friendly, the gym was clean and well maintained (better than most gyms at hotels ive been to), the beds were comfortable, and the decor was nice.

Cons:
They charge you $14.95 for 24 hours of wifi. And you can only use up to 2 devices.

name: J.D. Stone
text: Nice hotel. Didn't stay the night and wasn't there very long.

name: I AM
text:
If I could give this hotel a zero star, I would. An absolute embarrassment to the Sheraton brand, the franchisee should be ashamed. From the moment we walked in, it did not feel like a Sheraton, NOR a 4 star. The layout in the lobby was akward and crowded. Seemed like the entire guest list was huddled in the lobby trying to use the free WiFi. I mean how could you blame them though with such a ridiculous price of $15.00 per night. Who charges for WiFi anymore? Especially in an apparent 4 star? Elevators felt like something out of  a horror story. Clicks and clanks the who way up. Lobby felt like I was from the abandoned set of Three's Company. Dated. Filthy thick dust all along the ceiling. Skylights and windows had never been cleaned since the hotel was built in think. Musky smell, probably due to the fact that the pastel (yes pastel) multicolored carpet had never been shampooed. And then there was our room - where to begin...
1) water stains from an old leak on the ceiling 2) Filthy windows with drips of bird feces splatter on a window that didn't open.
3) Wall paper that was beginning to peel off
4) Doors that must have been recycled from an old demo somewhere in the wharf. They did not fit whatsoever and would allow light to beam-in through the gaps all night.
5) No fridge in room
6) No water pressure in shower
7) $60.00/night parking
8) Horrible sound insulation
9) Found and killed one of the most disgusting spiders I've seen in years.
10) Smoke smell coming in from adjacent rooms, but to be honest, we can't blame the hotel for that as they can't control the actions of others, but just thought it would be worth a mention.

This is just not a 4 star, and this particular Sheraton really shouldnt advertise such. Plus this place DOES NOT warrant a $300.00/night  price tag, especially when the Holiday Inn just steps away offers FREE WiFi and a Continental Breakfast at $250.00/night

The staff was good, and after complaining to the front desk lady, she did what she could by giving me a $50.00 credit to spend in the hotel caf√©. I could tell her hands were tied, as she appeared to want to do more but (I'm assuming) she'd have some explaining to do if she did. I've worked in the service industry before, and if I was a betting man:
a) the owner is cheap and ONLY profit driven b) corporate has no idea in just how horrible disrepair and dated this truck-stop, motel-like place is in, and;
c) there is no pride within this particular property as this they DOES NOT represent the Starwood Brand.

What a disaster...

name: Quan Nguyen
text: Expected a 4 star hotel but this is more of a run down place.

name: Constantinos Michael

name: I AM
text:
If I could give this hotel a zero star, I would. An absolute embarrassment to the Sheraton brand, the franchisee should be ashamed. From the moment we walked in, it did not feel like a Sheraton, NOR a 4 star. The layout in the lobby was akward and crowded. Seemed like the entire guest list was huddled in the lobby trying to use the free WiFi. I mean how could you blame them though with such a ridiculous price of $15.00 per night. Who charges for WiFi anymore? Especially in an apparent 4 star? Elevators felt like something out of  a horror story. Clicks and clanks the who way up. Lobby felt like I was from the abandoned set of Three's Company. Dated. Filthy thick dust all along the ceiling. Skylights and windows had never been cleaned since the hotel was built in think. Musky smell, probably due to the fact that the pastel (yes pastel) multicolored carpet had never been shampooed. And then there was our room - where to begin...
1) water stains from an old leak on the ceiling 2) Filthy windows with drips of bird feces splatter on a window that didn't open.
3) Wall paper that was beginning to peel off
4) Doors that must have been recycled from an old demo somewhere in the wharf. They did not fit whatsoever and would allow light to beam-in through the gaps all night.
5) No fridge in room
6) No water pressure in shower
7) $60.00/night parking
8) Horrible sound insulation
9) Found and killed one of the most disgusting spiders I've seen in years.
10) Smoke smell coming in from adjacent rooms, but to be honest, we can't blame the hotel for that as they can't control the actions of others, but just thought it would be worth a mention.

This is just not a 4 star, and this particular Sheraton really shouldnt advertise such. Plus this place DOES NOT warrant a $300.00/night  price tag, especially when the Holiday Inn just steps away offers FREE WiFi and a Continental Breakfast at $250.00/night

The staff was good, and after complaining to the front desk lady, she did what she could by giving me a $50.00 credit to spend in the hotel caf√©. I could tell her hands were tied, as she appeared to want to do more but (I'm assuming) she'd have some explaining to do if she did. I've worked in the service industry before, and if I was a betting man:
a) the owner is cheap and ONLY profit driven b) corporate has no idea in just how horrible disrepair and dated this truck-stop, motel-like place is in, and;
c) there is no pride within this particular property as this they DOES NOT represent the Starwood Brand.

What a disaster...

aus diversen Gr√ºnden nicht bereut,
dieses Hotel mit seinen ca. 530 Zimmern ausgesucht zu haben.

Die Sheraton Hotels haben eben einen bew√§hrten Standard,
der uns noch nie entt√§uscht hat und
hier hat mal wieder alles gestimmt,
was man sich von einem guten Sightseeing-Hotel w√ºnscht.

Zentraler f√ºr alle Sightseeing-Touren geht es nicht.
Fast alles ist fu√ül√§ufig innerhalb von wenigen Minuten erreichbar.
So ist z. B. der lebhafte Pier 39 im Fisherman's Wharf Viertel nur einen Block entfernt.
Auch der Wendepunkt der ber√ºhmten ‚ÄûCablel Car‚Äú ist nur wenige 100 m entfernt.
Von dort aus, kann man dann weiter zu den vielen weiteren Sehensw√ºrdigkeiten der Stadt,
wie etwa zum legend√§ren Chinatown oder den Gesch√§ften des Union Square fahren.

Alles in allem haben wir hier im ‚ÄûSHERATON FISHERMAN'S WHARF‚Äú,
eine hervorragende Unterkunft mit angenehmem Komfort und
einem sehr pers√∂nlichen Service (Danke John R.), der z. B.
uns nicht nur fachkundig beraten hat, sondern auch unsere W√ºnsche
-so weit es m√∂glich war- ber√ºcksichtigt hatte.
Unser Dank, gilt auch den Vor-Ort-Experten vom Concierge-Schalter,
die uns hervorragend beraten und wertvolle Tipps gegeben haben

Auch das ansprechende Hotel-Ambiente, hat uns super gefallen.
Besonders erw√§hnen m√∂chten wir noch,
die gem√ºtlichen am Hoteleingang befindlichen Sitzm√∂glichkeiten,
sehr romantisch mit offener Feuerstelle (siehe Foto),
um den Tag noch mal Revue passieren zu lassen.

Auch der Au√üenpool, ebenfalls mit einer st√§ndig brennenden Feuerstelle,
hat uns sehr gut gefallen.

Da wir eine ‚ÄûSheraton Club Karte‚Äú hatten, konnten wir auch,
in der leider nicht allzu gro√üen Lounge, kostenlos Fr√ºhst√ºcken.
Und auch der Internetanschluss war kostenlos.

Sehr teuer fanden wir die Hotelparkgeb√ºhren und auch das Fr√ºhst√ºck.
Aber beide Posten, kann man auch in direkter Hoteln√§he viel billiger bekommen.

Zusammenfassend ist festzustellen,
dass wir mit dem Hotel (Zimmer, Service, Hotelatmosph√§re) und seiner super Lage/Umgebung,
SEHR ZUFRIEDEN‚Äú waren und w√ºrden jeder Zeit wieder
ins ‚Äû‚ÄûSHERATON FISHERMAN'S WHARF‚Äú,‚Äú gehen,
allein auch, um sich mal wieder etwas ganz besonders zu g√∂nnen.

F√ºr uns, ein erstklassiges, und exquisites Hotel ‚Äúof the first rate‚Äù.

name: Troy Walker
text: Centrally located in Midtown, Best Western Midtown (formally known as Howard Johnson Los Angeles) is an average hotel in a less than average area. While it was recently renovated, the new Best Western Midtown is barely up to par with other Best Westerns in California. While it has some extra amenities such as Direct TV and a gym, the parking structure is severely inadequate, the area is quite noisy, and the rooms and service are average at best. Customers should expect that they won't have an official parking spot and that the parking staff will have access to their cars and will either move them without notice or be blocked in. While the hotel is within walking distance to downtown LA, it is at the intersection of two very busy streets causing noise at all hours of the day and night. The surrounding areas would also probably be considered 'suspect' to those from other areas. While convenient, the location doesn't outweigh the cons of the hotel and the Best Western Midtown would be far from my first choice of places to stay on a trip to southern California.

name: Ryan Sawadichai
text: Pretty good Korea town location at budget friendly rates. Most importantly, the rooms are recently (as of 2016) renovated, which means that the inn feels a lot nicer than many of the other budget inns. King rooms feel almost as nice as a Holiday Inn and everything inside the rooms is pretty clean. Will definitely stay again for Korea town.

name: Rachel Dixon
text: Comfy room with everything you could need. I was only here for a quick night but the staff was friendly. Looks to be recently renovated. Bed and pillows provided a good night's sleep.

name: Juliana K
text: The room was comfy and good enough space for placing the suitcases. I quite like the food of free breakfast - packed sweet rolls, breads and corn flakes. Simple is the best. Btw, the waffle iron was surprising me that I could made a waffle by myself!

name: Kevin Yi
text: HoJo was a good place. The facilities are spread out through the floors such as ice on the 2nd floor and laundry on the 3rd. Rooms are spacious to an extent with a very comfortable set of blankets. My only qualms would be the continental breakfast. It's adequate for a meal with many people but the food Is decent. Not an outstanding meal. Most is prepackaged with 3 types of cereal: raisin bran, fruit loops, and corn flakes (not frosted flakes). They do have a waffle maker though. Overall experience: satisfactory.

name: Jared Dong
text: Conveniently located in Koreatown, the Howard Johnson was a good value. Clean, upgraded rooms, but very noisy.  I guess you can't fault the hotel for their patrons, but the adjoining neighbor got locked out of their room very early in the morning and tried to break in for over an hour with kicking and punching of the door.  Management didn't really care when we complained.  Otherwise, it was a decent hotel.

name: Dave Wollenhaup
text: Limited parking, they double park to accommodate. Clean rooms. Noisy location, you can hear cars in your room. Also noisy hallways and noisy doors.

text: Rooms were clean like the website shows. Service was ok . Parking lot was small and seldom spaces available.  My first night i had to park on the street and move my car by 8am or face fines . There is another parking lot down the street if you dont mind walking around in a bad neighborhood . I was charged a one hundred dollar deposit after the room was paid for the day of check in.

text: Very spacious room, beds and bathroom looks pretty clean, location is right at the heart of koreatown and I love how they have their own parking garage plus a security guard during night time.

text: Great location and very clean. Staff was very friendly. Big downside, the beds were not soft at all. Almost felt like a mattress pad on top of a very sturdy cardboard box.

text: Decent room, clean, and maintained. Great beds to sleep in, very comfortable. Parking can be a little challenging when they are busy.

name: Z M
text: just a night stay. if you need a clean hotel this is your only option with a fair price. the staff is polite. i do not expect ritz carlton for hojo pricing. i will stay here as ofter i need to be downtown. great coffee bars near by.

name: Missy Boyd Cohen
text: The room was a little smelly, like mildew, but the beds were comfy and the free parking made it worth it. Close proximity to all downtown LA sights via the metro.  Good stay for the price

name: Steven Hale
text: I stayed at the Koreatown HoJo twice with the stays a week apart, at the beginning and end of a business trip. Very pleased with the whole service. Check-in was quick, with a specific mention for Travis who was exceptionally friendly and knowledgeable of the local area. The two rooms I stayed in were well equipped and very clean. The bed was large and exceptionally comfortable with plenty of good pillows - possibly the best hotel bed I've used in a long time! Standard service includes free WiFi, free continental breakfast including cook-your-own waffles, and also free parking. The central location has many restaurants nearby - Taylor's steakhouse, Denny's, IHOP, plus all the usual fast food burger joints and of course the many Korean BBQ.  The only complaints I would have is that the car park and breakfast room are rather small - I stayed during a quiet period but I imagine if the hotel was full during peak periods it could become busy and rather difficult. One night was quite windy and the bedroom windows rattled noisily. Likewise the extractor fan in both bathrooms seemed to do little except make a lot of noise. Only little niggles, and I'd still definitely stay here again on my next visit. For the price, location, and service you really can't go wrong.

name: Paul Cielo
text: Great service and speedy checkout. Would recommend to a friend

name: James Clifford Frederick Welch
text: If I could post 0 stars I would, because I have not felt more condescended by a Hotel Manager than David at the local Koreatown Howard Johnson. The internet connection was pitiful, he claimed that the only room available was the one he gave me on the 4th floor facing 6th street. NOISEY. I was awoken by a symphony of sirens every couple of hours each night of my stay, but that's not even the worst. They do not offer smoking rooms (massive bummer if you have to climb 3.5 flights of disgusting stairs to smoke outside), And, even though he claimed it was the only room left, I don't recall seeing any other guests stay there once I checked in. He wouldn't allow my mother to pay over the phone, so we had to do it over email (a little strange). In the end, I checked out kinda bummed that the hotel manager had given me the room with the worst chance of sleep. But, had also had over charged my moms debit card by 100 bucks. When I called to ask him to reverse it he claimed it was the banks fault and to talk to them about it, despite the fact he charged 328.70 on 5/28 at about midnight AT THE BEGINNING OF MY STAY. Since then, David has continually hung up the phone on me, I have even brought it up with HoJo's customer care on-and-off, time-and-again, only to be told basically "we'll get back to you". If it was a MOTEL6  manager they would have been fired immediately for failing to correct an overcharge. The only way that I could have gotten a $100 fee is if I had a "cancellation" but unless checking out before 11AM is considered a cancellation, there is nothing in the "hotel policy" he tried to use as defense to charge me over 300 dollars for two nights in a room he knew I wasn't going to be able to sleep in. I have been taken advantage of before, but I never felt so backhanded and insulted for calling out what could have been an honest mistake but the only thing that was honest about him was that "doesn't know anything about that". Maybe somebody who knows about how to treat customer complaints should be running ANY hotel, let alone one that is supposed to get my 3-star rating. AVOID THIS HOTEL AND IT'S MANAGER DAVID before he tries to take your credit line or bank account hostage and then tells you that he can refuse service because their policy says it's okay if you've already paid. JUST STAY AT THE MOTEL 6, OR ANYWHERE ELSE. Never again will any Howard Johnson get a nickel out of me. I still haven't got my refund. Their company also outsources their Reservation Toll-free number to the Philippines who have no idea what state LOS ANGELES is in; I am morally against outsourcing of American customer service jobs, because nothing makes an angry customer happier than hearing the thickest of an Alabaman Drawl ask how to help you. Anyways, yeah avoid this place, head for the hills. Don't give this David guy a cent of your hard earned dollar. I'm sure that somebody will care at some point, and that somebody's job is to care about making sure people or Managers who trick people into paying for 3 nights get terminated and possibly sued. I'm not sure, I'm just a 21 year old kid from San Diego who knows BAD CUSTOMER SERVICE, and THIEVERY when I see it.

name: P. Walker
text: The buildings are old. They will tell you there is no noise and it is a good place to live. They will tell you the rooms are clean. They will tell you they will help in any way possible. Here is the reality: Lots of drug dealers, transients and crazy people live here. The guy above me makes noise all through the night doing god knows what and constantly wakes me up. They keep telling me they will move me but always forget. The rooms are filthy and smell really bad. I have had the air conditioner on the whole time I have been here just to get a bit of fresh air. The WIFI is horrible and I can't even use my hotspot so no watching videos online. The rooms are uncleaned and have roaches laying around (corner in the bathroom pic). THE PLACE IS ICKY. YOU WILL NOT WANT TO TOUCH ANYTHING. Don't believe me, look at the pics I uploaded. The bathroom, carpet, and whole place is filthy. They charged me $366! for a week for this place. I could of gotten A MUCH, MUCH, MUCH better place somewhere else for 50-100 bucks more. You will pay big time for trying to save a buck like I did. TRUST ME DO NOT COME HERE. name: B FPV
text:
Had a road trip and found this motel on booking dot com. After driving onto the lot I realized that this place is far closer to the Las Vegas strip than expected. The check-in process was extremely pleasant and quick, because the motel was relatively empty the front desk staff gave me an amazing room - corner location on the top floor, overseeing the MGM Grand! Excellent room, clean, organized and really cool location.
the MGM is across the street and within 10 minute walking distance. If you are interested in exploring the Southern part of the Strip you can easily book this motel.
Wifi: This place has free WIFI. It is not the fastest but it works for the applications I had in mind (email, booking websites, flight status checks via the Delta app). I wouldn't rely on this Wifi for HQ youtube videos, but with the Las Vegas Strip across the street you won't need Youtube anyway!

Staff is amazing and professional, I highly recommend this motel for single travelers, business travelers, couples without kids (with kids there might not be enough space but maybe they also have larger rooms).

name: David Cluster
text: If you stay close to the main office up front and on the 2cd floor you'll probably be pretty free of critters like bed bugs, water bugs and roaches. I stayed for 2 nights and went directly back next door on the 2cd floor of the front area where the convenience store, pool and check in are located. Except for the Airport which surprisingly is pretty quite you can lift the mattresses move whatever you need, but I stayed for 3 months and had not one bug in my room. The ice machine is at the back of the pool. If either starts to run out try to hit the store on the grounds. You can go next door to the liquor store and get big bags of ice if your patient. Remember 2cd floor and up front at Motel six. Have a great time in law Vegas and please do come back again......April Cluster

name: Passion Desire
text: I always come here. The staff and maids arr great especially Todd :) Its 5 mins from the strip and close to pretty much everything else like the blvd mall, fashion show mall, college, airport, stores etc. i like that this room is 18+. On a normal day it costs around $45. On the weekends the price shoots up ! On a regular weekend day i paid around $85. But during events it skyrockets to $120-$160. I feel like if im staying numerous days i should receive some type of discount. Because $120+ for this room is waaaaay overpriced, so i usually dont stay on weekends. But they have laundry and snack/soda machines. Theres also an atm in the lobby. Option for a cash deposit would be great too. Since ive stayed here ive seen only 1 or 2 bugs in my room, but i keep my drains shut. The rooms are super small but for $45 you cant beat it. Just wish there was a mini fridge. But they always let me rent a room and i never have problems here, so 4 stars

name: Irina Grigorieva
text:
(Translated by Google) This motel is NOT recommended. Perhaps, in the building where the reception is located, you can feel safe, since it is open around the clock and there are video cameras, but in the buildings behind it it is scary. Despite the fact that the Strip and some cool casino hotels are within walking distance, a rather deserted area begins behind the motel. further is the airport. Old furniture, dead plumbing, lamp TV and noisy air conditioning. You can turn off the air conditioner, but it will be stuffy. And it is better to keep the door closed at night. And not only at night, but also in the morning and during the day. We were faced with a situation when our acquaintances, with whom we were traveling in a group, were attacked early in the morning. An African American with a spray can burst into the room, took a backpack with valuable things. At 8-50 am (!). The police then came to the call, of course, but it was too late. name: Lyndsi Winer
text: Isn't even called the IP anymore I think it's changed names twice since being called this.  But regardless the big blue roofed hotel across from Caesar's is one of the best spots to stay. 1. once you figure out how to get to your room, which may be a bit confusing at first, you will find it's an easy in and out hotel to get to the strip as fast as possible.  It's not a super deep hotel so it's about a 3 min walk out once you hit the casino floor.  2.  It's always dirt cheap to be central strip and stay here.  3.  They have balconies so if you want to get some fresh air most of the rooms towards the back have a great view and lots of fresh air.  I've never felt the room was dirty and I feel it covers everything you need for the trip.  I've stayed here quite a few times for as little as 18$ a day to 75$ so really not too bad if you think about it!  Great spot, it's worth a chance!

name: Katie K
text: If I could give this place even more stars I would. My family came here for the week and had an amazing time! We were in the tenting area right in front of the lake.  We had an excellent view.  The sunsets here are insane! Whether relaxing at the pool or by our tent site, all 3 of us had a great time! Also, the hospitality here is great.  Everyone very friendly.  Thank you so much for the lunch on July 4th, that was a great surprise! Will definitely be coming here often. So peaceful.
resp:
Thanks so much for the kind words Katie! We love our campers like family.
So glad you enjoyed your stay! Hurry backüôÇ

name: Nick Nyhan
text: Pulled in there after Niagara Falls visit. Really great view of the Lake and beautiful trees and grass areas and playground for kids to play. Dave the manager made sure we were good and told us they have been investing to make things even better. Good place for weddings.  Lots of different size buildings on the site but spread out nicely.
resp: Thanks for the review and kind words Nick! Happy campers are our goal everytime!  Safe travels and be sure to come back soon! üôÇ

name: JustGoFlyVinnie
text: I can't rate this hidden gem high enough. We got the royal treatment from the owner and staff. Jenn checked us in and was excellent in letting us get our way, moving us to our desired site, and coming to check on us. I ran into a guy name Dave, who was cleaning bathrooms, and I started asking him about the campgrounds. Who would guess the owner was cleaning the bathrooms. But if you saw the bathrooms you would understand his attention to perfection and his amazing creativity. He invited us for coffee and we got a personal tour. Their plans for this campground and conference center are extraordinary and very exciting. I think it's going to have a huge draw, and so beautiful. You can see Toronto in the distance, across Lake Ontario. Enjoy the photos. I intend to post a video soon.
resp: Thanks so much for the kind words!  We hope to see you again soon!  Safe travels!üôÇ

name: Matt Carroll
text: We rented the hotel for a company party for this past weekend and I could not be more happy the owners, staff, and everybody else there. Very very very accommodating to things.   I would recommend this place to anybody who is either looking to just get away for the weekend or a week long stay. It really is an amazing place to go to.  Thank you again Niagara shores for the wonderful weekend and we will definitely see you again next year.
resp: Thanks for the kind words Matt, but the pleasure was ours. Thank you all, cant wait to see you back here next year.

name: Russell Larsen
text: What a Jem. Great place to host a wedding or party. The owners really have this place looking great. Definitely check them out, including the bed and breakfast. Also RV spots overlooking Lake Ontario with some great views.

name: Philip Martin
text: This is a very nice place to camp they have houses that can fit 20 people in it, they have  cabins , cottages, even a hotel for those that dont like the woods feel.  They have a  in ground salt water  pool.  They also have RV hook up.  There is 50amp hook up so those big buses RV'S can hook up overlooking the Lake Lake Ontario. Thier trails are so nice and kept up.  The campground is family oriented, friendly people.

name: John Wagner
text: Booked an RV site in October.  Very nice private campground.  The owners are in the process of making improvements, so will be even better in the future.

name: Stitch the Cat
text: This place is great for whatever. You name it they can help your accommodation needs.  At the temple of this reviews they are still renovating for opening in the spring but we stayed in the Bed and Breakfast and got to discuss the future plans with the owners and we became very excited about booking further vacations with them because they have big plans for the former youth retreat / conference center.  It is great to get away and unwind from the daily stress.  I am sure when this destination is fully open and complete it will be a real jewel for Olcott, NY. name: Chris Shimmin
text:
Reservation only. $25 minimum per person.

Great views of downtown and the empire. Not crowded with the reservation only.

name: Gurleen K
text:
This rooftop is absolutely beautiful! You feel like you are sitting somewhere in the Mediterranean.  It's a great date spot as well as a place to get awesome cocktails.

I came here with some girlfriends and we had a great time!! We came just to get drinks but we ended up staying for dinner because the vibe here is amazing!! This is the most beautiful rooftop and you will get the most amazing photos as well!!

When you get out of the elevator you get greeted by the most friendly staff (rare in NYC). Then they take your temperature with a super cool photo monitor (you have to see it to believe it!).  There is hand sanitizer at every table and the servers are wearing masks. We appreciate the level of high safety measures being taken!! Thank you!!

Love this place and it should definitely be on your bucket list if you are in NYC.

IG- @traveleen_gurl

name: Nick Felker
text: I went to the rooftop bar, which is inside the hotel (farthest-to-the-right elevator only). I found it to be a pretty good place to drink in the city, with a good view of Penn Station and much else of the city. The drinks were a bit expensive, in particular as I had to reserve a table ahead of time. I would probably go here again though.

name: michelle rodriguez
text: Amazing service, drinks and snacks. Great views & increible decoration. Not crowded like other rooftops in the city. Would highly recommend for a date or just to have social drinks.

name: Ashlyn Belding
text:
Cocktails were average - not too memorable. I switched to wine after trying a variety of ~5 cocktails. The waitress was obviously up selling us as soon as we got to the table - offered shots (which we got), prompted us to get better alcohol instead of house (which we did); and yet service was still extremely slow. We had to ask for water multiple times. Our food came out before drinks.

Mushroom pizza was pretty good; better than the pepperoni, tomato and pepper one (tasted like Subway).

Instagramable place; cool views; but overpriced and service sucked. Would go back if the night option presented itself but not necessarily dying to go back.

name: rennae francis
text: I saw this place on Instagram and love rooftops so I said why not?! You have to make reservations in advance and pay a deposit but it gets added to your bill. The menu isn't that intense so we stuck with the pizza but the bar will make whatever drinks you want. The staff is super friendly and honestly it feels like the Hamptons in Manhattan. Should definitely check it out. They also give you a huge bowl of spicy cashews if you order it. We didn't finish half of those cashews lol but they were good.

name: Average Socialite
text: Amazing new rooftop in NYC in Chelsea - Hamptons themed with amazing drinks, food & views! COVID measures in pleace. Make sure you make a reservation and be prepared to take a ton of pics!

text:
Great ambiance and amazing views of the Empire State Building. Wait Staff very friendly and I was glad I picked this venue to celebrate my birthday.
Management did work with me concerning my photographer and I am grateful. It was sort of tricky trying to have memories professionally captured for my Pre-Birthday Soiree, and trying to abide with the venue restrictions on photography!!üôè

Complete pass. Arrived at the place based on an Instagram review. They must have paid for it because the place is a C at best. The only thing keeping it from a F- is that is ia a roof top.

To many amazing options close by. Go elsewhere.

We arrived around 530p on a Saturday.¬† The place was at less than 50% occupancy.¬† Yet, they insisted on placing our party of three at a two person setup. Rude.

Beyond this, they had the windows shut and did not have the ac on. The place was a sauna - break a sweat hot. We opted to leave.

Ezy, the floor manager, was rude to my party and the one in front of us.¬†¬† Customer service is not his strong suit. When we left another couple left as well and the only sizable party they had left as well.

To add insult to injury the uniforms are horrendous. Very 1950s nursing home. I don't know who the are catering to.

Pass.

name: Shane Hatcher
text: I just can't explain how terrible this experience was for six nights. I didn't expect much from a Roadway Inn or of any Choice Hotel for a matter of fact. But this place takes the cake for the worst at service and the absolute nastiest room that I have ever stayed in. My military accommodations in Kuwait in Iraq were more attentive and clean. You shouldn't use this place if you have small children or a compromised immune system for the fact that you are likely to end up in the hospital. The place is filled with pubic hairs and cigarette smoke. The staff is miserable to include the highly impaired manager whom was clearly under the influence of something strong. Tony's attitude is award winning and demeaning. The personal insults and disregard of people with disabilities was just shameful to witness. Choice Hotels will be hearing from me and in particular about Tony's questioning of a Desert Storm Veterans disability. Tony the nasty receptionists whom has a personal calling to involve herself in others conversations and unwitting ability to propel insult toward customers valid complaints. I just can't explain how unbecoming this experience has been.

name: Jesse Teitsworth
text: DO NOT STAY HERE. Easily the worst "hotel" I've ever been to. Floors were dirty. Shower did not drain.  Bathroom was filthy. The toilet seat was left up when I got there. A colleague found nail clippings in her room. The beds were rock hard. I don't think the sheets were clean. Several rooms had people living in them. It's the only place to stay for about 40 miles, but in hind sight, it would have been worth the drive to avoid it. Truly terrible place.

name: Dani Madden
text:
If I could do lower I would and I think all the negatives speak for themselves as well as the constant changing hands shows horrible ownership but here is my personal experience.

I just had my daughters 5th birthday party at the pool. We talked with them face to face with a Penny in May in June she emailed me which I have. I called said wait for me to figure out whether or not we want food (only cake was allowed everything was to be bought from the kitchen which I understand) but she said "it was on the books"

Well day of the party July 9th show up no one knows anything about it. There was garbage all around the pool (pretty normal for this place) no chairs or tables, water everywhere not even close to the pool, & the kitchen was closed so we couldn't get food if we wanted. Only perk the man working the desk was helpful.

Called to complain to the company that I spent that much money on renting out the pool for a private event to have it go so bad. They sent me to the assistant manager who then told me this was my own fault. There needed to be a down payment and signed contract. I have witness with me as well as emails to prove there was no mention of either. He said she never would do that and I should of called to do it. Basically calling me a lair.

I am going to call corporate again because now I really want my $150 back after this.

name: Mark Student
text: My wife and I have been here twice now, and it's a really great bed and breakfast experience. Diana and Jennifer are great, and Diana makes the best breakfast. It's really so good. Both are very friendly and hospitable. The rooms are all different with different styles. But they're all well kept and comfortable. As a guest, you don't feel forced to socialize, but you're always invited to. The location is great for touring wineries or breweries as it's right in the middle of the "trail". It's also close to the town with all the restaurants. Really, if you have any interest in a bed and breakfast, you'll really like it here.

text: This resort is definitely one of a kind! They are currently celebrating 150 years of being in business. There is so much history that really made me feel like I was time traveling. The place is enormous and rich in beauty, and their service is beyond warming. I have never been in a lake so clean and pure. I strongly recommend going for a couple of days to get away from the city.

Take a day trip and wander around, spend the night or even a wknd just to get away from the hustle and bustle of everyday life! I'm sure you won't regret it!!

name: Steve Oelheim
text: Not at all what I expected. We were assigned this hotel while in the area for a hockey tournament. Surprised that we'd get a "resort and spa", but whatever. Then we looked at the pictures online, and it definitely looked a bit dated. Expectations were tempered. It vainly wasn't the fanciest place ever, but it was decent. No, the accommodations weren't the most modern. The regular rooms were a touch small, but they were clean and the balconies were nice. We had friends who got a suite, which was much roomier. The pool was EXCELLENT.. very large, and they even have a lifeguard on duty. Front desk staff wasn't the friendliest, but we talked to the manager a couple of times, and she was fantastic. Don't eat at the restaurant, the are CLEARLY not prepared for more than 2-3 tables at a time. We ate dinner and breakfast there, and service was painfully slow (though the good was pretty good). Very hockey-friendly hotel, had no problems with our kids playing knee hockey. They also gave us a complimentary party room for a team party. All in all, it was everything I'd expect from hotel at $109/night.

Checkout is at 11am, and at 10:35 the maid was knocking on our door and trying to get in, thankfully we had locked it. If you say checkout is 11, then she shouldn't be making her rounds til after that unless we checked out. Staff at front desk absolutely not personable. Ok I mean I guess‚Ä¶

Don't believe all of these nasty reviews because this place isn't THAT bad. They have good wifi so that's a plus. But in my room they only have one outlet and it is in the corner of the room. It's good though like me who is only staying the weekend and is visiting someone in college. So in conclusion, I believe that people are just exaggerating and that this place is a ok place to stay.

EDIT: I thought this was a good place to stay. I had written that review a hour after we got the key. That was before the beds. They were so uncomfortable I couldn't even sleep. text: Saddest part about my review is that I come here VERY often. My last visit I wasn‚Äôt to satisfied with the cleanliness of my bed and sheets. Recycling sheets and pillows after a long time of being used, is completely unsanitary. A low budget hotel or not, there‚Äôs certain requirements when running an establishment like so. Also, I just currently came here and I‚Äôve never heard of a hotel that doesn‚Äôt let you check in until 4 pm especially when check out for previous over night guests is at 12 pm. No one can wait in the lobby. I took 2 hours to get here and I‚Äôm pregnant, the receptionist explained that I couldn‚Äôt wait until check in time which was only a hour to come after my arrival. This is unacceptable and unprofessional. With the amount of funds this hotel receives everyday there is no reason that you guys still have yet to buy new things, upgrade items and at least train your workers with common courtesy. Honestly, if this problem persists... as a active member of the community board, I will gladly bring this problem to their attention and push for a thorough investigation. As I said it‚Äôs understood what type of low class establishment you guys are running but professionalism and hospitality should still be a must especially when I‚Äôm spending my money here faithfully!
resp: Thank you for taking the time to provide feedback, Meqren. Cleanliness and sanitation are of the utmost importance to us, and we'll certainly be more diligent in assessing linens for the future. We always want to provide a comfortable stay and helpful service, so I'm sorry you weren't better accommodated on your most recent visit. You can trust that we'll address these issues for the future. Providing a wonderful guest experience at a great value is what we're all about. -Arlene James, Manager

name: Diane W
text: Room was very nice, had a coffee machine, microwave, refrigerator, blow dryer and iron in the room. The pillows were super comfy!  We slept great. However, the parking garage was being redone  which left only a small lot to hold 8 floors of guests.  Between Wing Fest and multiple weddings in the area it was VERY hard to find parking.

name: kali hash
text: Stayed here about two weeks ago. Came to the bar for happy hour drinks with my boyfriend. Monica was tending bar and gave us the greatest customer service I have ever received. She was so funny and friendly. We are now regular customers of hers. The food was great too. I enjoyed the calamari and cheese sticks at happy hour price. We looked into the coffee bar and wine bar but we didn't eat there. There was a patio and fireplace.. As well as wine on tap! I love this place and the whole staff is great. Makes you feel very welcome.

name: Elvis S.
text: Plenty of drunks slamming doors late at night on a Friday night. But the room was cozy and decent. The staff are helpful and kind. I'd go back.

text: We had breakfast with family visiting from out of town. The service was relatively quick and the food was good. The cinnamon French toast was delicious and I enjoyed the breakfast skillet.

name: Christopher O'Drain
text: Not too shabby. I don't really have any complaints about this Holiday Inn (I stay at alot of hotels for business)- judging by the previous comments and ratings, this hotel must have come under new management recently. Staff was fast and easy to deal with, no room issues, no noise or sleep issues. Appears to be a very busy hotel (lots of guests, weddings, events etc). I didn't get a chance to check out the onsite bar and restaurant, but I did hear good things about it. I'd recommend this hotel.

text: Upon arriving I stepped out onto broken  glass. I mentioned it to front desk. That night and the next day it was still there. The Continental breakfast was to laugh at. The toaster did not work and everything was scummy looking .  It seemed like Russian men were running it.  I could not recommend this Days Inn.

name: Bridgett Donnelly
text: I was only in town for 1 night and wasn't looking to spend a whole lot. Lesson learned. When I got there the manager was at the front desk, playing on his cell phone, and didn't even bother to acknowledge my existence for a good 2-3 minutes while he finished what he was doing. No  'hello', 'how are you', nothing. I got a frank "Checking out?" "Yes, at 3:30p I am checking out." "Huh", messes around silently with the computer for another 1-2 min, "Are you Bridgett? I need your credit card". We get checked in and he tells me I'm going to need to wait while he tried to find the housekeeper because she was supposed to call him at 3 to tell him rooms were cleaned but "apparently has chosen not to today". Professional. Comes back 5 minutes later to tell me I can go to my room. The room. Wow. Carpets look like they hadn't been vacuumed in weeks. Room smelled like musty, stale cigarettes. The window curtains were stained with God knows what (probably uncleaned blood for the brutal attack that happened there 6/5/2016-as i learned later). Around midnight, there's a knock on my room door. By the time I get to the door, gone. I make sure the door is double locked from the inside and get back in bed. Then I can hear someone outside the room with a key trying to get in the room. I get up, throw the door open, and asked "what can I do for you?" This poor guy apologizes, saying he saw the door tag on the door and informed the desk clerk that someone was in this room but they insisted the room was empty and told him to try getting in anyways. Wonderful. Beds suck and are uncomfortable but at this point are the least of my concerns. The next morning I woke up to staff outside my door very loudly complaining about another customer that had just checked out. When I checked out the woman at the front told me I was all set and asked "Did someone come to your door last night? We don't even have you in our system". Really? Because the guy clearly knew my name and took my money. "Oh yeah, that was the manager. He can be a bonehead." Absolutely unreal. The entire stay was disgusting from services to conditions of the room. I'll never waste my money with Days Inn again.

name: Yuri Zahn
text: The entire place smelt of cigarette smoke. The sheets were rough, and the bed was lumpy. Our bathroom light was out and could not be replaced (maintenance was off). Plus. when I went to report this and check out the staff was rude. It was as if I was bothering them. I will never stay here again.

name: Amy Warner
text:
Located close to the jail and airport, this Days Inn is horrible. The building reaks of cigarettes, as if the hotel only became non-smoking an hour before our arrival.

In the room nothing worked or was connected. You could only watch TV of you could figure out the proper way to hookup and program the cable box. Air conditioning was an almost laughable myth. First you have to plug it in yourself. Then it doesn't cool the air, just blows the hot air gently around the curtains. Don't bother trying to call the front desk. Your phone phone, clearly marked as being from a room on a different floor, has a dial tone, but none of the keys work. It would matter anyway, there is no maintenance staff to fix the air conditioning, out phone. While there was a mini fridge and a microwave, they had be negated for some time. Freezer burned food had become one with the tiny freezer unit in the fridge.

The bathroom was usable, but only just. For a family of four, only two bath towels, one hand towel, and one wash cloth were provided. The empty tissue box was left in the wall dispenser with no replacement available. One roll of toilet paper was provided on the back of the toilet, as the two holders were broken. Black mold is clearly visible on the drop ceiling and in every corner.

The bed was a long size as advertised. Being extra soft and springy, the toddler found it worked best as a trampoline.

Moral of the story: the Hilton, a block closer to the airport, is worth the $45 more a night.

name: Will Warner
text: Complete dive of a hotel. The entire building, including the non-smoking room my family had, reeked of old cigarette smoke, the bed had no support left in it whatsoever, the air conditioning did not work (either to cool air or even move it around!), the window did not open, and even if it could, the screen was destroyed, bathroom fixtures were rusty and some broken, grounds were unkempt and overgrown, and the location, while nice and close to the airport, is across the street from a youth correctional facility and next door to a car rental and shipping depot. This was nowhere near worth the $99/night rate for the park and fly package. I will gladly spend more for future trips to never stay at this dump ever again.

This gem is smack in the middle of the hills of Gore Mountain, and the fall colors are a spiritual experience.

Room , bed had no blankets on them , ceiling had water stains , towels were the size for a child , no coffee in the morning down stairs , room only had one cup no creamer, big disappointment !! name: Daniel Ladd
text: My girlfriend and I wanted to take a romantic weekend in North Creek and the Copperfield seemed like a nice hotel given the photos and extravagant prices. We arrived at the Inn and it was sub-par, the rooms were out of date, and things were starting to fall apart. Our mirror in the bathroom was held together by duct tape and the towel rack fell off the wall when I removed a towel. We paid a lot of money for a "package deal' that came with an $80 gift card to their two "amazing" restaurants. We were excited to go to Lorenzo's which was supposed to be the higher end restaurant, but it was never open. Since Traveler's was the only other place to take the gift card we had to go there, the food was pretty good but the service was absolutely horrible. There were four waitresses standing around talking the whole night while one poor waiter tried to keep up with every table. They also forgot to tell us that neither of the restaurants are open on Sunday so we were left with $30 on the gift card that could never be used. Lucky enough we got part of that gift card money refunded but it took some work. You can find a much better quality hotel for less money.
